        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We will observe with one baseband in the high resolution FDM mode, dual polarisation, but binned by a factor 8 to achieve a spectral resolution of 11 km/s over a total bandwidth of 5400 km/s. The total width of the CO(3-2) line is expected to be 170 km/s, so we will bin the data to improve the signal to noise. The remaining three basebands will be used in TDM mode in order to achieve good continuum sensitivity.
</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>To optimise our detection efficiency, we choose to use a low spatial resolution of 1 arcsec, which will not resolve out the CO gas. There are no issues with missing emission that is more extended than the largest recoverable scale.
</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>This proposal aims at detecting the CO(3-2) line redshifted to 103.09 GHz observable with ALMA band 3. The target coordinates are on the host DLA-galaxy.

Using the H-alpha luminosity measured in our SINFONI observations, we derive the star formation rate (SFR) assuming the Kennicutt (1998) flux conversion corrected to a Chabrier (2003) IMF. For the galaxy host responsible for the DLA toward Q2222-0026, we measure a dust-corrected SFR of 37 solar masses per year. Based on the SFR-L_FIR relation of Kennicutt (1998), this translates to L_FIR=2 x 10^11 L_sun. Using the CO-FIR correlation (Solomon &amp; van den Bout 2005), we derive an expected minimum CO flux of L_CO=4 x 10^9 K km/s pc^2. We thus should reach a total molecular mass of the order 2 x 10^10 M_sun assuming a Galactic CO to H_2 conversion factor of 4.6.

Assuming a fully thermalised gas, we therefore expect a flux of about 137 mJy km/s or a flux density of 0.9 mJy at 5-sigma for a 150 km/s line (as indicated from H-alpha). Using the ALMA sensitivity calculator with 36 antennas, we get 43 min on the target, corresponding to a total observing time including calibration of 1.18h. This set-up will provide a SNR of about 5, which is needed for our scientific goals. We have checked that the background quasar that has a small angular separation from our target is fainter than this limit, using a non-detection at this sky position in the FIRST survey. We therefore expect it to be faint at millimeter wavelengths as well, and hence there are no dynamic range issues.
</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
